title.narrative: OUTPUT 5: QUALITY NUTRITION SERVICES

description.narrative: Stronger capacity among public and private sector and civil society actors to promote nutritional well-being of children, adolescents and women, which contributes to Cross-Sectoral - Planning And Programme Reviews, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition (Covid), Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition In Early Childhood (Covid), Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid), Supply And Logistics. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children, adolescent girls and women of childbearing age access and utilize nutrition services, nutrient-rich foods and supplements to improve their well-being

description.narrative: UNICEF;investment in the national capacity and systems for improved quality and delivery of essential nutrition services yielded results in 2021. Atotal of 2,056,479 children under five years benefited from the lifesaving Vitamin A supplementation, 133,744 children 6-23 months had improved diet through use of micronutrient powders, and over 2.5 million adolescent girls 10 to 19 years benefited from anemia prevention Iron Folic Acid Supplementation. Additionally, 10,437 children with severe acute malnutrition, received lifesaving treatment, while 349,160 mothers and care givers of young children were provided with nutrition counselling. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:07/01/2022
